				 TCS net rises to Rs 1252cr
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 TCS managing director and CEO S. Ramadorai (right) with chief operating officer N. Chandrasekharan in Mumbai on Monday. (Fotocorp)																								Mumbai, Oct. 15: Tata Consultancy Services (TCS) posted a consolidated net profit of Rs 1,251.6 crore for the second quarter ended September 30 compared with Rs 1,018.7 crore a year ago, a rise of 23 per cent. 																								The companys second quarter revenue stood at Rs 5,640 crore, up 25 per cent year-on-year. Sequential revenue for the quarter was up 8.4 per cent.																								TCSs operating margins went up by 77 basis points, including a 1.09 basis point positive impact of pricing and productivity. Offshore leverage added another 36 basis points. The forex movement and a wage hike had a negative impact of 30 and 117 basis points respectively, while rupee hedging added 79 basis points. 																								This includes a 102 basis point gain in other incomes, officials said. The company had earned revenues of $2.7 billion in the first half of this fiscal by improving profitability for the second quarter. 																								On a standalone basis, the company has posted a net profit of Rs 1,147.11 crore for the quarter compared with Rs 931.32 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous fiscal. Total income is Rs 4,681.5 crore. 																								Chief executive officer and managing director S. Ramadorai said, Fifty per cent of our revenues have come from non-ADM businesses such as BPO and infrastructure services. We see this business growing at a double-digit rate. Full services play, early entry into new markets and our global delivery model have paid us rich dividends. A focus on new geographies like Latin America and Asia-Pacific has given us good growth. Our focus will be new geographies, the BFSI and manufacturing sectors. 
